The first virtual operator will come to the Czech Republic this year.
Probably.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is fairly developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
However, here we still need something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It's probably not gonna be long before he gets here.
That Czech operators are part of the most expensive in Europe, we have already written it on mobile.cz.
The rest also confirmed this by the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTU) which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is among the most expensive in the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in regulating roaming rates, it is likely that there will be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, text messages sent from abroad will be cheaper than sending them from home.
How can prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lack of competition that you really want to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, because we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that there is an extreme competition in the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTU), Pavel Dvořák, has already expressed that there is no place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It may be true that for a classic operator with his own network he no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the virtual operator's entry into the mobile telephony market brought a marked decline in prices, at which the classical operators also had to react.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile to the UK market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It has been shown that there is room for such operators and that they can succeed.
However, there is no need to look for examples too far away.
In February of this year we informed you about the exterior of the Mobilking virtual operator in Poland.
Only after half a year did this operator get over 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighbouring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking, the Penta group is located which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic owns U:phone.
The advantage of virtual operators is possible to focus on many more specific target groups.
In addition, in order for them to function effectively, they are sufficient with many less customers than a classic operator.
They do not bear relatively high costs in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world this kind of virtual operators are usually profiled with low costs - they offer cheap SMS calls and messages that, however, often contrast with the offer of more adjusted services.
Thus, for example, Tesco mobile in Great Britain offers at least half of the cost of SMS with respect to competition.
However, as shown by the example of Mobilking in Poland, it can also be a good blow to bet for a trivial goal group.
This operator is specifically addressed to the man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - he is the operator who likes and who can be trusted," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say if such a concept as Poland could fit into our country.
Vodafone spokesperson Miroslav Čepík says: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of the offer of services, it is relatively saturated"
There is no possibility in the Czech Republic, mobile operators say.
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be any virtual operator in the Czech Republic that will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic it does not seem too hopeful.
It's about Mobilking's launch in other countries in our region," said Jana Studniková, spokesperson for the Penta Financial Group.
He indirectly ensured that current mobile telephone operators in the Czech Republic definitely did not turn their backs on this idea.
Instead, they try to do everything possible to ensure that no potential competition emerges.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step further to become a real competition for Phone O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in this, so that we can offer our customers not only fixed telephony services but also mobile telephony.
And the sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have repeatedly met with all Czech mobile telephony operators.
With some of them we have managed to move forward at the meetings," said the group spokesman, Pavel Kaidl.
So maybe they're wasting better times.
It seems that, for non-official information, the first official operator would have to arrive possibly by the end of the year.
But for now its appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At this point we believe that the situation is ideal for the appearance of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market in comparison with others is a very specific market.
So far no one has addressed us with some complex and serious project in this field," said Vlastimil Sršeň, spokesman for Telefónica O2.
The specificity of the Czech market refers to other operators.
T-mobile spokesperson Martina Kemrová, in accordance with the opinion of O2, adds: "To this day we have not registered any viable commercial project that, bilaterally beneficial, can continue to develop."
And he adds: "In the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find any virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this point we should already have on the table a specific contract that could be studied in as short a horizon as possible."
Vodafone is more focused on meeting the own requirements of a 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepiký adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this concerns the allocation of expenditure and infrastructure.
We consider it precisely the greatest contribution from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this field is in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for a fast internet in the mobile."
Offices responsible - with operators of sheep and meat
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would increase competition which would lead to a lower price and thus to a lower profit.
Then why facilitate entry to competition?
When operators want to get something, they're able to pull out of the same rope, proof of that is the grip when U:phone came up.
Perhaps the biggest pressure on ČTU was at the time of the entry of U:phone by the T-Mobile company.
It is witnessed by public information available on the ČTU website.
But right now U:phon serves as an argument why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds: "In addition, it is not long ago that the competitive environment in the mobile telephony market was opened to a fourth operator.
With regard to the nature of the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would be for him and, above all, for his large services."
That is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging because of the absolute lack of interest of the Czech regulatory body.
This is not just the position of the ČTU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tenders (UOHS).
However, she expressed her typical attitude to this problem.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile telephony market would be possible after a contract on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile telephony operator and a virtual operator is concluded.
To date, no agreement has been concluded as the offer of potential stakeholders was not sufficiently interesting for classical operators," Kristian Chalupa, of the Department of External Relations of the UOHS, added to our question.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For offices which should represent the interests of consumers, this is more than a consideration, apart from that they should note that no one takes advantage of their position on the market.
Especially when Kristian Chalupa adds: "In the foreign country where virtual operators operate normally we can observe that their market entry contributed to the lower prices of mobile telephony services"
Obviously, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market media and the lowering of prices is not within the interest of the UOHS.
Indeed, the dramatic shock in all this case lies in the dissatisfaction resulting from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is a coincidence is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of petrol in the gas pipelines as it is clear that it is work of chance and a hard struggle for competition.
"The Office has not found any signs of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators have a dominant position, therefore they do not have a corresponding rise in liability in their market operations.
The tools needed to open the mobile telephony market to virtual operators, rather, are missing, as well as telecommunications regulators," Chalupa added.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many conflicting points.
There is obviously an analysis of relevant markets developed by the ČTU, according to which telecommunications is from the point of view of commercial tendering a single market.
In this type of market, of course, none of the Czech operators have a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer another view - to get a virtual operator out is always necessary to agree with the network administrator.
And the mobile phone operator - with all his logic - has the monopoly of his network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must be necessarily dominant.
And if this argument is not accepted, at least for UOHS it should be a warning that three mobile operators appear attractively similar.
Current complaints from stakeholders (including GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with operators there are many similar obstacles.
Loading responsibility in the ČTU is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications from which UOHS washes hands in this whole matter.
We've already met with him in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the Telecommunications Act for the extension of ČTU's competition in the field of commercial tenders was recently tabled, even when a number of experts promised that the situation would improve.
The representatives of UOHS must know this perfectly, but it is clear that their interests are elsewhere.
Everything's fine when nobody sees
At the same time, unconsciously it continues to work as well as a pseudo-virtual operator that in Czech mobile networks there are already a few.
They are companies that put their own prices on mobile telephony services which, however, are only one part public.
This is usually about companies that are engaged in multi-level marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile telephony services.
Usually only a few chosen get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business client of the company carrying a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions in all Czech mobile telephony operators prohibit such resale.
"If cases such as those mentioned could be found to be infringing on the terms of the contract that could be translated at the end of the collaboration with the company concerned," answered Martina Kemrová to the question about this problem.
But it is quite unlikely that an activity of this kind carried out by mobile telephony operators would reach responsible people.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned above, thousands of customers may be involved.
None of the operators are opposed to this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they achieve nothing despicable gains and, at the same time, - unlike the true virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepíký warns us of the possible problems: "The law allows for speculation of this type, however, the services of this company are used only by a significant percentage of customers.
These should also accept that the SIM card of your phone is not in your name so they cannot absolutely dispose of it as a normal customer of operators."
This is exactly what the ČTU should think at least strange.
In addition, there is a new question for UOHS.
If mobile telephony operators surround their eyes in this type of procedure, why block the virtual operator's entry?
It is necessary to add that UOHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activity and, if you do not want to, should not be satisfied with the operators' explanations that they have no idea of this story and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive?
As already made clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market brought a significant decline in service prices.
At the same time, in virtually all countries where the virtual operator emerged, classical operators tried more or less to protect themselves from this eruption.
The arguments used by these were almost all identical - too small, a market, possibly too saturated, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, regulatory bodies have now intervened and in none of the cases have defended operators but their clients.
Whether with formal measures or informal pressure they managed to emerge the first virtual operator and with it they started to appear more.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Authority all this happens as if it were a burning key.
For our experience, we cannot help but be impressed that the confusion of the attributes in these cases is good for them.
But we won't despair.
If this information between builders is correct and the virtual operator really reaches these lands, then the Czech mobile phone market is probably beginning to move again.
If any of the operators allows any virtual mobile telephone operator to enter, it will be difficult for the UOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling more expensive than the rest of Europe.
