Prague MDD brings us on Wednesday for the first time with the chip
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, is written in the history of the Prague Transport Company on the date when the first passengers enter the metro, tram and bus with an electronic voucher in their pockets instead of a paper ticket.
This can be purchased at this time by nearly one hundred thousand people who have the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy the 30-day, 90-day and annual bonus (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and at the same time load it on their chip card in the info centres and stations of the transport company at the metro stations, Museum, Mostek, Nádraži Holesovice, Angel, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
Bonuses can be bought from yesterday on the website of the transport company, www.dpp.cz.
The service, until the afternoon, was used by more than four hundred people.
Those who start using the Internet as a form of commerce can definitely start to forget the ticket sales points in the metro stations, where so far they had to regularly queue to get a regular ticket.
The bonus is purchased online, and the Opencard card is recharged in one of the 13 branches of the Municipal Library.
"In these places there is available to passengers a window with prepared staff that helps interested people with the purchase of the internet and also with the recharge of the bonus purchased on their card," said project spokesperson Martin Opatrný.
In addition to the library, it will also be possible to recharge the electronic bonus on Opencard in the exhausting automatic machines that are located in some metro vestibules.
How are these exhausting machines?
They are red, they remind us of a ticketing machine, and the passengers will probably have already been fixed in them at the stations of the metro of Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are now five in the city but at the end of the year there would have to be eighty," Opatrný said.
The bonus is controlled by the machine instead of the driver
The use of the machine, which will start working tomorrow, is simple.
Just enter in it the Opencard chip card and the previously paid bonus will only be charged on it.
Electronic bonuses from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
In other words, on bypass trains and bus lines from 300 to 499 that mainly use the inhabitants of the central Bohemian localities.
"In the trains attached to the integrated transport of Prague there are reviewers equipped with a reading card that will help confirm the validity of the time and the bonus zone," explained the control of the tickets, Filip Drápal of the Ropid organization, which establishes the timetables for the collective transport of Prague.
Circuit buses have their reading cards mounted on the driver’s cap.
When entering it is necessary not only to show the card to the driver but also to accompany it with the Opencard at the place intended for it on the side of the Box.
With this, the driver controls the validity of the bonus.
"If the passenger needs to check the validity of the bonuses there is nothing easier than to ask the driver for this information," Drápal said.
Passengers who do not travel on roundabout buses and do not remember when they finish the bonus validity can be directed to the exploding machines where the cards are recharged.
