The interview - Blood is safe again
Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday its 10th anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Hema-Québec has become one of the world's safest and most effective blood suppliers.
And above all, he regained public confidence that he had been seriously paralyzed by the scandal of the blood contaminated in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and public discontent, in February 1994, the Government of Canada conducted a public survey, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, which aimed to clarify the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster would no longer occur.
While Judge Krever was delaying his relationship, some provinces then set up a committee aimed at planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee carried out this mission.
As a result of the reports by Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Hema-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all the other provinces and territories.
" In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, nearly 38 per cent of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
After having made many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work during the years that followed, we have regained public confidence," he said, proudly saying that at the beginning of 2008, about 94 per cent of the Quebec population had confidence in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Décary nevertheless recalled that " trust is extremely fragile " .
Since its creation, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle on 28 September 1998.
At that time, we attended in Europe the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of the mad cow disease, a new variant of the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, account Décary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
Then we rely on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when we do not know and when a serious disease can arise from that, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we introduce measures of exclusion.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of persons who had remained in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
But a few years ago, it has been demonstrated beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us so that the precautionary principle applied had meaning."
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV detection technique appeared on the market: the tests of nucleic acid that enable donors to directly detect the presence of the virus in the blood rather than antibodies against the virus, in which the tests used so far were based.
Nuclear acid tests allowed to cut the period between the time the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period within a period of less than a week.
We have thus substantially reduced the risk that certain donors are infected without knowing it and that we cannot detect them.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, every 12 million people are at risk of receiving blood contaminated by HIV.
"This means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
Thus, since Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, more than 24 years will pass before a case of transmission of HIV through a blood product occurs.
I think today you can receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover your health without any concern," says Hema-Québec head.
" Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of the Reunion that, for example, the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
She has to be constantly vigilant," said Dr. Décary before stressing that, in addition to a secure supply, Hema-Québec must also provide sufficient supply.
" The needs increase because the population is ageing.
Since anti-cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need to inject red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has implications for the network of blood donors, which in the medium term regroups only 3 per cent of Quebecis eligible for blood donation. "
However, all persons with good health, aged 18 and who meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
In the medium term, 14% of those who propose their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they travel in a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
" With this 3%, we have managed to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Poor people are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this donor network as they grow older and can no longer donate their blood.
But it's hard to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to keep them and encourage them to be regular donors.
Since the present life is very slow, we rarely find time to spend an hour to donate their blood," says Francine Décary.
With a budget of $297 million annually, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissues, including bone ingestion, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public blood bank of the umbilical cord in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was previously considered biomedical waste is full of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
" We have celebrated a few weeks ago, the introduction of our thousandth blood sample from the umbilical cord and is expected to extract more than a thousand of these per year.
We should start to propose it for ingestion at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this blood take program as very popular.
" Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot enjoy this, " since Hema-Québec has no resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
