Psychology of the answers: Why do we spend more money?
The participants in the auctions are willing to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York discovered the neurological bases - economics of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study published in Science magazine, people do not want to lose in skills such as eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists have tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" by means of experimental auctions.
One of the volunteer groups played lottery, the other participated in a auction and as long as it was examined through the functional magnetic resonance system (fMRI) the active areas of the brain of the participants in the experiment.
In both games the participants could earn money, but during the auctions, where it is a fundamental element to bet more than the other, losing the game intensified the operation of the complex called stratum located below the brain cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the "self-prime" mechanism of the nervous system.
Thus, according to scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a prevention to avoid an intense reaction of the stratum.
To support their theory, the economists of the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment, three groups betting against one person under different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the real value of the product in question, and its members were betting.
Another group was also promised that if they won, they would receive $15 more in prize.
On the other hand, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in the event of the loss of the auction, even the members of the group lost that money.
So the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, by checking the neurologists' hypothesis, the members of the group that played "against failure" were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the "winner" group.
"These results cannot be deducted from any previously existing economic theory.
Because those so far explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods have helped resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation" - established Andrew Schutter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should you go to your doctor?
In the world some 50 million people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the main causes of death.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated because many of the sick do not know that they are infected.
The name of hepatitis is the common name of different liver diseases caused by viruses.
Symptoms appear to be very common; they are characteristic of liver infection and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases caused are very different.
Hepatitis virus depending on the pathogen is spread through two main forms: hepatitis A and E via food (e.g. with water or contaminated food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body humour (sperm, vaginal humor, saliva).
It is recommended for travellers to be protected by a vaccine against virus A and B, and against C no vaccines.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two or three weeks after eating the infected food, it is manifested by a poor general condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After this appears in the skin and in the white of the eyes the jaundice, the excrement becomes clear, the dark urine and healing can last even two to three weeks.
Each year a million people die in the world of cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to estimates, only one in ten infected people receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can produce liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most people do not know that it is sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys the liver cells and often the first symptoms appear only 20-30 years later.
Therefore, early recognition, systematic medical control, is very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently there are about 200 million people in the world who suffer from chronic hepatitis C.
Since this disease can also be detected with routine laboratory control, it is worth consulting with the family doctor when experiencing some unknown symptoms.
The disease has a cure if it is discovered in time, it is possible to eradicate the virus from the body, so you can eliminate the infection and prevent cancer.
On 30 September, it was the World Day of Hepatitis, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of their early recognition.
Does it hurt less those who believe in God?
According to a recent study, religious faith has a calming effect that also alleviated the death of martyrs of Catholicism.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed how religious belief influences human pain - reported the British newspaper Telegraph.
In the context of this unique experiment, they applied electric shock to 12 Catholic believers and to the same number of atheists, while all were looking at a painting by the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the technique of scanning the human brain, it was possible to verify that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
This experiment is the first of the series of studies in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the different departments of the University also participate alongside academics.
The analysis took place in the following way; they fixed a chispanzee instrument at the patient's left hand, which applied the electrical shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look at it in two paintings; the 17th-century work of the Virgin Mary and the Lady of the 15th-century Armor of Leonardo da Vinci.
The researchers hoped that the performance of the Virgin Mary would cause a certain religious spirit among the faithful, while choosing Leonardo oil because it was not too different from the other, and thought it had a calming effect.
Patients spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, receiving 20 electrical shocks in four successive parts during that period while observing the painting of the religious theme or the other.
The Catholics claimed that when they looked at the Virgin Mary they felt in "security" as "protected" people "they calmed down and peace reigned in their hearts".
When they observed the picture of the religious theme, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any such impactive image you can achieve a similar effect with atheists too, you just have to find the right image.
"We should find the portrait of a person who feels very positive, like a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
The Anglican bishop Tom Wright celebrated the outcome of the investigation.
"The exercise of faith should and in many cases really change our personality" - added Wright.
After these amazing results, there remains one question: What effect would the Madonna of Leonardo or another painter of her size have on the regulation of pain?
Would the vision of a high-quality Virgin Mary cast even better results?
