In August 2008, national industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to last month's prices and by 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 prices - the Central Statistics Office (CSH) reported.
Industrial export prices rose by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 per cent compared to the previous year.
As a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent over the previous month and by 3.2 per cent over the previous year.
Industrial sales prices increased only to a minimum, with 0.1 per cent.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry increased at a minimum, by 0.1 per cent compared to July.
The highest price increase occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 per cent), due primarily to an increase of 4.6 per cent monthly of bags and belts and an increase of 2.5 per cent of footwear.
The highest price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical production branch (1.6 per cent).
Price decreases were made in the petrochemical sector (1.4 per cent), in the production of electrical machinery and instruments (0.9 per cent), as well as, to a minimum, in the wood processing sectors (0.1 per cent).
They did not change the prices of paper manufacture, publishing and printing.
The rest of the processing industry recorded an increase in prices between 0.2 and 0.9 per cent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water, which represent an important weight in domestic trade, an increase of 0.3 per cent was recorded in August, first of all as a result of the increase in official prices from the first of July.
In a 12-month comparison - in the domestic sales of the processing industries - the higher price increases were recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 per cent).
An increase of 13.2 per cent was observed in the metal processing sector, while in the food, beverages and tobacco industry, of decisive weight, an increase of 11 per cent was observed.
Price decreases were recorded in the textile industry (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and instruments (0.3 per cent).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 per cent.
During the year in the processing industry overall, prices increased by 10.2 per cent.
Electricity, gas, heat and water prices exceeded 18.7 per cent of previous year's prices.
In August, among the different domestic trade sectors, the highest monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) was recorded in the investment property sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, in the energy and intermediate sector prices there was no change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the highest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediate industry (16.8 per cent).
A fall of 6.8 per cent was recorded in consumer goods producers and 1.4 per cent in investment goods.
The export prices of the industry calculated in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 per cent.
